Part 1

"Please... side... please... give a little side..."

The voice wasn't loud. Yet it somehow managed to cut through every other noise in the crowded casualty corridor. 

A man arguing at the billing counter stopped midway, his receipt hand frozen in the air. The ward boy pushing a heavy oxygen cylinder paused, letting the iron cart rest against the wall, to look back. Even the tea seller outside the glass entrance, who spent his days shouting at the rickshaw stand, lifted his head from his boiling kettle, watching the entrance.

The stretcher wasn't moving. A rusty wheelchair had been left carelessly across the metal ramp, blocking the entrance swing doors. 

The old ward boy pushing the stretcher shook his head, muttering under his breath. "Every day," he said, pushing the wheelchair aside himself with a sharp, heavy metallic scrape that echoed off the damp concrete walls. "People think hospitals have roads wider than highways. They leave their carts anywhere."

The girl walking beside the stretcher smiled faintly. It wasn't because she found the comment funny; she simply had no energy left to react. 

Her left elbow was bleeding, the cotton sleeve of her blue top torn and stained with grease and road mud. Grey dust still clung to her palms and under her nails where she had tried to pull the old man off the road. She hadn't even thought of washing them since the crash.

The old man lying on the stretcher looked strangely peaceful. His eyes remained closed, his face completely relaxed under the harsh, flickering glare of the corridor tubelights. 

A thin stream of dried blood had travelled from his forehead, across his cheek, to his left ear, turning dark and crusty near the lobe. His white cotton shirt was torn, almost completely brown near the shoulder from the dry dirt of the road where the bike had dragged him. 

One rubber slipper still remained on his right foot, held loosely by the worn plastic strap. The other slipper had probably remained somewhere on the road near the bypass, kicked away in the impact.

The girl suddenly stopped near the swing doors of the casualty ward. She bent down, removed the remaining slipper from his right foot, and placed both slippers carefully beneath the frame of the stretcher, aligning them side by side on the wire rack.

The ward boy looked at her, his hand resting on the metal bar of the stretcher. "You know him?"

She shook her head, wiping a smudge of dust from her cheek. "No."

"Then why..."

She simply smiled, her fingers touching the cold railing. "It doesn't look nice... wearing only one slipper."

The old ward boy looked at her for two seconds, his face blank. Then he quietly resumed pushing the stretcher.

"Casualty!" the nurse shouted from the counter, without looking up from her thick register. "Case?"

"Road accident," the ward boy said.

"Name?"

The ward boy looked at the girl. The girl looked down at the old man's face, trying to find a name she knew. "...Budha Baba," she said.

The nurse continued writing, her metal-nibbed pen scratching against the rough paper of the register. "Full name?"

"I don't know."

Now the nurse looked up, her glasses sliding down her nose. "You don't know?"

"No."

"Father's name?"

"I don't know."

"Age?"

"Maybe... seventy."

"Address?"

"I don't know."

The nurse slowly closed the register, the thick cardboard cover making a flat, dusty thud. "You brought an unknown old man to the hospital? Who will pay for the medicines? Who will sign the police report?"

The girl nodded. "He was bleeding on the road. I had to bring him."

"So?"

"I brought him," she said simply. 

The nurse looked at her as though expecting another explanation, some long story of relatives or a passenger. None came. The girl's face was calm, her posture quiet despite the torn sleeve and the dried blood on her arm.

The ward boy interrupted, leaning against the counter. "Madam... bike hit him near Saraswati Government School. Hit and run. The driver ran toward the highway."

The nurse sighed, her hand resting on the desk. "Every day..." She reopened the register, her pen hovering over the page. "Relationship?" 

The pen remained waiting over the empty column. The girl didn't answer immediately. 

"Relative?" the nurse asked.

"No."

"Daughter?"

"No."

"Neighbour?"

"No."

"Then?"

"I run an NGO nearby."

The nurse wrote it down in the column: *NGO Volunteer*. "Sign here."

The girl signed without reading the printed text. The stretcher disappeared inside the emergency room, the double doors swinging shut behind it. 

Only then did she realise she was still holding the old man's walking stick. Nobody had noticed it during the entry.

She looked at it carefully. It was an ordinary bamboo stick, smooth near the handle where his palm had rested for years, and worn thin near the bottom from the gravel roads. 

Someone had tied a tiny strip of red cloth at the top, perhaps to recognise it quickly in a crowd. She quietly kept it beside the ICU door, leaning it against the wall as if the old man would immediately ask for it after waking up.

Inside, the emergency room had already become another world. "BP dropping," a voice called. "Pulse?" "Seventy... no, sixty-eight..." "Suction." "Gauze." "Another IV line." "Move, move." 

One patient cried behind a blue curtain, calling for water. Another abused the hospital staff. Somebody's child wouldn't stop coughing. A woman fainted after seeing blood on the floor. A ward boy searched for a missing oxygen mask. 

Everything happened together, a loud, ongoing noise where nobody had time to notice anyone else's problem.

Except the girl. She stood outside the half-open glass door. Every time someone crossed between her and the bed, she instinctively shifted sideways to see whether the old man was still there, as though he might quietly disappear if she lost sight of him.

"Attendant," a voice said behind her.

She turned. The receptionist stood holding a yellow admission form. "Admission details."

She followed him to the desk.

The desk had a landline phone, a steel pen stand, a half-eaten packet of biscuits, and a rectangular rubber stamp that he moved to one side and then moved back again without using it. On the wall behind him was a laminated list of fifteen document requirements for new patient admission, printed in size-eight font. Most of them were illegible from this distance.

"Name," he said.

Again she stopped. Finally she wrote: *Budha Baba*.

"Age."

*Approximately 70.*

"Address."

*Unknown.*

"Phone."

She wrote her own number. The next column remained blank: *Relation with patient.*

The receptionist tapped the table with his pen. "Madam..."

She held the pen, thought for a moment, and then slowly wrote: *Human*.

The receptionist stopped, his pen hovering. He looked at what she had written. He looked at her. Then he looked at the laminated form guide on the wall, as if checking whether *Human* was somewhere on the official list of permissible relationships, and finding it predictably absent.

"This is not an essay, madam. Write proper relation."

She looked at him. "I know. But he has no family."

"Then write NGO," the receptionist said, shaking his head and picking up the rubber stamp — which he then set back down again. "Or 'known person.' That column has been filled with worse things than 'known person.'"

She quietly struck the word out. Then she wrote: *NGO Volunteer*.

At that exact moment, the old Nokia phone inside her handbag started vibrating. She looked at the screen. *School Office*.

She answered immediately. "Hello."

"Didi... children know," the voice of the school headmaster said from the other end.

"What?"

"They know Baba met with an accident. The auto driver told them during the lunch break."

"Who told them?"

"The auto uncle," the teacher said. "They're crying in the yard."

She closed her eyes, the hospital smells of bleach and iodine filling her head. "I'll come later, master-babu."

"No... they're refusing lunch. The school cook is sitting with the plates."

"I said I'll come," she said, and disconnected.

The phone vibrated again almost immediately. *Milk Anna*. He wanted to know if he should bring the evening supply to the shelter. Then, *Temple Pujari*, asking if Baba would come for the evening prayers. Then, *Old Age Home*, where Baba usually spent his Wednesdays. Then, *Vegetable Market*, where the vendors were waiting. 

Every caller asked exactly one question: "How is Baba?"

She answered every one of them exactly the same way. "Doctor is treating him. He is in the casualty."

Within twenty minutes, the corridor had started changing. 

A flower seller arrived carrying two unsold garlands of marigolds, his fingers still wet from the stringing. A school teacher came directly from her class, her chalk-dusted handbag still on her shoulder. 

An old postman arrived, still wearing his faded khaki uniform and carrying his leather mail bag. A tailor, a bus conductor, a fruit vendor pushing his cart near the gate, and a college student carrying a heavy backpack—all arrived.

Nobody knew each other. Yet every one of them walked directly to the same ICU door. 

Nobody asked where to stand. Nobody spoke loudly. Nobody demanded updates from the nurses. They simply waited, sitting on the floor or leaning against the wall.

The receptionist slowly looked up from his computer screen, then looked toward the security guard near the door. "Who is this old man?"

The security guard shrugged, his hand resting on his wooden baton. "No idea. He sweeps the temple verandah sometimes."

"But..." He looked outside at the corridor. "...the crowd keeps growing."

[End of Part 1]